  "prompt": "How much of demonetized money, might not come back to the banking system?",
  "response": "The amount of demonetized currency that may not return to the banking system can vary significantly based on several factors, including public trust in the banking system, the effectiveness of the demonetization process, and the overall economic environment. \n\nWhen a currency is demonetized, individuals may choose to hold onto their old notes without exchanging them, either due to a lack of awareness, distrust in the banking system, or simply as a means of hoarding value. Historically, in instances of demonetization (such as India's 2016 demonetization of \u20b9500 and \u20b91,000 notes), a certain percentage of the demonetized currency remains unreturned.\n\nIn India, after the 2016 demonetization, it was reported that about 99% of the demonetized currency returned to the banking system, which means that around 1% did not. However, this figure can vary in different contexts and countries, depending on the specific conditions and implementation of the demonetization policy.\n\nTo get a precise figure for a specific instance or country, one would need to analyze data from central banks or financial authorities post-demonetization.",
